chapter={{lang|de|Die Stellung der Frau: Spuren indogermanischer Gesellschaftsordnung in der Sprache}}|editor-last=Sch\u00e4rer|editor-first=K.|title=Spuren lesen|publisher=Chronos|year=2007|isbn=978-3-0340-0879-2|location=|pages=97\u2013115|language=German}}\n{{Proto-Indo-European language}}\n\n[[Category:Indo-European culture| ]]\n[[Category:Proto-Indo-Europeans|Society]]\n[[Category:Bronze Age]]\n[[Category:Society by ethnicity]]\n", "name_user": "Azerty82", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-Indo-European_society"}
{"title_page": "List of Tales of the Unexpected episodes", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Tales of the Unexpected'' episodes}}\nThis is a list of episodes of the British drama series, ''[[Tales of the Unexpected (TV series)|Tales of the Unexpected]]''.\n\n==Season 1 (1979)==\nNine episodes.&nbsp; First broadcast: Saturdays on [[ITV Network|ITV]] \u2013 24 March to 19 May 1979\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | No. in<br>series\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | No. in<br>season\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | Directed by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | Written by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | Introduced by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | Cast\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #A92623; color: #ffffff;\" | Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|03|24|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Man from the South|The Man from the South]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Michael Tuchner]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Adaptation by'': [[Kevin Goldstein-Jackson]]\n| Aux2            = [[Roald Dahl]]\n| Aux3            = [[Angela Malcolm]] (Maid), [[Pamela Stephenson]] (Cathy), [[Jos\u00e9 Ferrer]] (Carlos), [[Michael Ontkean]] (Tommy), [[Cyril Luckham]] (Rawlsden), [[Katy Jurado]] (Mysterious Woman)\n| ShortSummary    = An American sailor is on holiday in [[Jamaica]].&nbsp; He becomes involved in a bizarre bet with Carlos, who loves to gamble.&nbsp; When the young man boasts about his cigarette lighter, Carlos offers him his Jaguar if the boy can strike his lighter successfully ten times in a row.&nbsp; But if he fails even once, if the boy does not strike it precisely, Carlos will cut off his finger.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|03|31|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Mrs. Bixby and the Colonel's Coat]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Simon Langton (television director)|Simon Langton]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Adaptation by'': [[Ronald Harwood]]\n| Aux2            = [[Roald Dahl]]\n| Aux3            = [[Will Leighton]] (Seamus), [[Richard Hampton]] (The Patient), [[Richard Greene]] (The Colonel), [[Michael Hordern]] (Cyril Bixby), [[Julie Harris (actress)|Julie Harris]] (Mrs Bixby), [[Alan Chuntz]] (Taxi Driver), [[Sandra Payne]] (Miss Pulteney), [[Frederick Farley]] (Pawnbroker), [[Vass Anderson]] (Master of Hounds)\n| ShortSummary    = Mrs Bixby is having an affair behind her husband's back.&nbsp; Her lover gives her a mink coat.&nbsp; She devises a devious plan to explain its presence to her husband.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|04|7|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[William and Mary (short story)|William and Mary]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Donald McWhinnie]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Written by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Ronald Harwood]]\n| Aux2            = [[Roald Dahl]]\n| Aux3            = [[Marius Goring]] (Dr Landy), [[Elaine Stritch]] (Mary Pearl), [[Frederick Farley]] (Baxter), [[Richard Hampton]] (Vicar), [[Jimmy Mac (actor)|Jimmy Mac]] (Dr William Pearl), [[Jane Paton]] (Nurse)\n| ShortSummary    = A widow is informed by her doctor that her husband's brain has been kept alive.&nbsp; The husband had always imposed a strict regimen on his wife and she now seeks revenge.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|04|14|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Lamb to the Slaughter]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[John Davies (director)|John Davies]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Written by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Michael Byrne (actor)|Michael Byrne]] (Patrick Marney), [[Brian Blessed]] (Detective Sergeant Jack Nolan), [[Susan George (actress)|Susan George]] (Mary Marney), [[Mark Jones (actor)|Mark Jones]] (Detective Sergeant Jameson), [[Andrew Fell]] (Uniformed Policeman), [[David English (actor)|David English]] (Plain Clothes Policeman), [[George Little (actor)|George Little]] (Samuel), [[Hugh Cross]] (Police Doctor)\n| ShortSummary    = Mary Marney, a devoted and pregnant housewife, is preparing dinner when her husband Patrick returns home from his job as a police [[detective]].&nbsp; He tells her that he is leaving her.&nbsp; Moving almost on autopilot, Mary fetches a [[Lamb and mutton|leg of lamb]] from the deep-freezer in the cellar to cook for their dinner.&nbsp; Patrick says he does not want dinner, as he is going out.&nbsp; In a trance-like panic, she hits him on the head and kills him.&nbsp; The police conclude that Patrick was killed with a large, blunt object, but are baffled when the murder weapon cannot be found.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|04|21|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[The Landlady (Roald Dahl)|The Landlady]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Herbert Wise]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Written by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Siobh\u00e1n McKenna]] (The Landlady), [[Leonard Preston]] (Billy Weaver), [[Anthony Dawes]] (The Clergyman), [[John Bryant (actor)|John Bryant]] (Mulholland), [[Jess Davies]] (Temple)\n| ShortSummary    = Billy Weaver, a young man from London, arrives at a guesthouse.&nbsp; He is greeted by the landlady, but his curiosity is aroused when he reads the guest book.&nbsp; He sees the names of young men whom, he remembers, had gone missing.&nbsp; The landlady tells him that she is a [[Taxidermy|taxidermist]].\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|04|28|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Neck (short story)|Neck]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Christopher Miles]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Written by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Michael Aldridge]] (Sir Basil Turton), [[Joan Collins]] (Lady Turton), [[John Gielgud]] (Jelks), [[Peter Bowles]] (Major Jack Haddock), [[Paul Herzberg]] (John Bannister), [[Carmen Silvera]] (Carmen La Rosa)\n| ShortSummary    = Lady Turton, an art collector's wife, is conducting a series of affairs, much to the disapproval of her resentful husband and their butler, Jelks.&nbsp; They have an estate filled with art; even the outdoor gardens have fantastical pieces of [[topiary]] and abstract sculpture.&nbsp; One night, while cavorting with Major Jack Haddock and making fun of her husband's beloved artworks, she finds her head trapped in a priceless piece of art.&nbsp; Sir Basil Turton asks Jelks to fetch him a tool with which he can free her head.&nbsp; Jelks brings him both an axe and a saw.&nbsp; After considering the problem, Sir Basil decides upon the axe.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|05|5|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Edward the Conqueror]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Rodney Bennett]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Written by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Ronald Harwood]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Joseph Cotten]] (Edward), [[Wendy Hiller]] (Louisa), [[Phil Brown (actor)|Phil Brown]] (F. Milton Willis)\n| ShortSummary    = A husband and wife adopt a stray [[cat]].&nbsp; The cat responds to the woman's piano playing to such a degree that she becomes convinced that it is the [[reincarnation]] of [[composer]] [[Franz Liszt]].&nbsp; The woman bonds with the cat, much to her husband's jealousy.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|05|12|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Dip in the Pool|A Dip in the Pool]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Michael Tuchner]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Written by'': [[Roald Dahl]]<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Ronald Harwood]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Jack Weston]] (William Botibol), [[Gladys Spencer]] (Sylvia), [[Bill Reimbold]] (Bill Wilson), [[Elaine Ives-Cameron]] (Sarah Grant), [[Davyd Harries]] (Purser), [[Michael Troughton]] (Steward), [[Jana Sheldon]] (Mrs Renshaw), [[Don Fellows]] (Renshaw), [[Paula Tilbrook]] (Maggie), [[David Healy (actor)|David Healy]] (Auctioneer), [[Ken Buckle]] (Sailor)\n| ShortSummary    = William Botibol, a man on a [[cruise ship]], takes part in a bet to predict how far the ship will travel in 24 hours.&nbsp; He calculates that he will win if the ship is delayed a little\u2014if, for instance, it has to turn back to collect a man overboard.&nbsp; To win by cheating, he waits until  a woman and he  are alone on the deck, and then he pretends to fall overboard.&nbsp; Unfortunately for him, the woman is not what he thinks she is.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 9\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|05|19|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[The Way Up to Heaven]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Simon Langton (television director)|Simon Langton]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Written by'': Roald Dahl<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Ronald Harwood]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Julie Harris (actress)|Julie Harris]] (Alice Foster), [[Angus MacKay (actor)|Angus MacKay]] (Walker), [[Julia Watson]] (Maid), [[Dulcie Huston]] (Hostess), [[Jeremy Longhurst]] (Driver), [[Brian Capron]] (Airport Official), [[Anthony Bailey (actor)|Anthony Bailey]] (Arthur), [[Roland Culver]] (Eugene Foster)\n| ShortSummary    = Mrs. Alice Foster has a pathological fear of being late.&nbsp; On the day of her holiday to [[New York (state)|New York]] to see their daughter, her husband, an inveterate and somewhat sadistic dawdler, torments her by making her late.&nbsp; To her relief, the flight is delayed and they make it on time but he continues to taunt her with his deliberations.\n| LineColor       = A92623\n}}\n|}\n\n==Season 2 (1980)==\nSixteen episodes.&nbsp; First broadcast: ITV \u2013 Saturdays 1 March to 14 June 1980\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | No. in<br>series\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | No. in<br>season\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | Directed by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | Written by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | Introduced by\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | Cast\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color: #060701; color: #ffffff;\" | Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 10\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|03|1|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Royal Jelly (short story)|Royal Jelly]]\n| DirectedBy      = Herbert Wise]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': Roald Dahl<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Andrew Ray]] (Percy Hayward), Susan George (Mabel Taylor), [[Timothy West]] (Albert Taylor)\n| ShortSummary    = A beekeeper becomes concerned when his wife tells him that their baby daughter is ill and losing weight.&nbsp; To help the baby gain strength, he begins feeding her [[royal jelly]].\n| LineColor       = 060701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 11\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|03|8|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Skin (short story)|Skin]]\n| DirectedBy      = Herbert Wise\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': Roald Dahl<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Lucy Gutteridge]] (Josie), [[Boris Isarov]] ([[Chaim Soutine]]), [[Donald Pickering]] (Gallery Owner), [[Peggy Ashby]] (Rich Woman), [[Sabina Franklyn]] (Young Girl), [[David Webb (anti-censorship campaigner)|David Webb]] (Chef), [[Derek Jacobi]] (Drioli)\n| ShortSummary    = An old street beggar, a former tattooist, was a friend of the famous artist, Soutine.&nbsp; On his back, he has a tattoo by the artist, which is now priceless.&nbsp;\n| LineColor       = 060701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 12\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|03|15|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Galloping Foxley]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Claude Whatham]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': Roald Dahl<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Adrian Breeze]] (Boy), [[Guy Humphries (actor)|Guy Humphries]] (Stamford), [[Wayne Brooks]] (Boy), [[Timothy Breeze]] (Boy), [[Clifford Abrahams]] (Boy), [[Paul Spurrier]] (Young William Perkins), [[John Mills]] (William Perkins), [[Anthony Steel (actor)|Anthony Steel]] (Man on the Train), [[Anthony Woodruff]] (Housemaster), [[Jonathan Scott-Taylor]] (Young Bruce Foxley), Colin Thomas (City Gent)\n| ShortSummary    = William Perkins is haunted by the bullying he received while at boarding school 60 years ago.&nbsp; While on a train, he is convinced that the man sitting opposite him is the [[bullying|bully]].\n| LineColor       = 060701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 13\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|03|22|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[The Hitch-Hiker (short story)|The Hitch-hiker]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Alastair Reid (director)|Alastair Reid]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': Roald Dahl<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Cyril Cusack]] (Michael Fish), [[Rod Taylor]] (Paul Duveen), [[John Forgeham]] (Policeman)\n| ShortSummary    = Flashy American Paul Duveen stops to give elderly Irish vagrant Michael Fish a lift in his new [[BMW]].&nbsp; Michael is a [[Pickpocketing|pickpocket]], which comes in very handy after his encouragement to Paul to break the speed limit has attracted the attention of a traffic cop on a motor-bike, who waves them over.&nbsp; After the cop has gone, Michael shows a happy Paul that he stole the cop's notebook and evidence, but before long, Paul will be anything but happy.\n| LineColor       = 060701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 14\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|03|29|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Poison (story)|Poison]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Graham Evans (director)|Graham Evans]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': Roald Dahl<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Robin Chapman]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Andrew Ray]] (Harry Pope), [[Judy Geeson]] (Sandra), [[Saeed Jaffrey]] (Dr Kunzru Ganderbai), [[Anthony Steel (actor)|Anthony Steel]] (Timber Woods)\n| ShortSummary    = This story is set in [[India]] during the time of [[British Empire|British colonialism]].&nbsp; Narrator Timber Woods goes to visit his friend Harry Pope.&nbsp; Harry is in bed, motionless, sweating, and in a panic.&nbsp; He whispers that a [[krait]], one of the deadliest snakes, is on his stomach, underneath the covers.&nbsp; He asks Timber to go get a doctor; Timber calls Dr. Ganderbai, a local Indian doctor.&nbsp; Timber and Ganderbai frantically try to get the snake off of Harry to save his life, but they find no snake on Harry; perhaps it has gone, perhaps Harry imagined the snake.&nbsp; When he realises this, Harry is so relieved that he attacks Ganderbai with racial slurs.&nbsp; The real poison in the room is not the snake's; it is the racist's.&nbsp; Ganderbai walks out of the room and tells Timber that Harry needs a vacation.\n| LineColor       = 060701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 15\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|04|5|df=y}}\n| Title           = Fat Chance\n| DirectedBy      = [[John Gorrie (director)|John Gorrie]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': [[Robert Bloch]]<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Denis Cannan]]\n| Aux2            = Roald Dahl\n| Aux3            = [[Katie Flower]] (Amateur actress), [[Peter Van Dissel]] (Amateur actor), [[Nigel Caliburn]] (Stage Manager), [[Carol Thornton]] (Woman in Audience), [[Geoffrey Bayldon]] (Dr Applegate), [[John Castle]] (John Burge), [[Sheila Gish]] (Frances), [[Miriam Margolyes]] (Mary Burge), [[Anthony Royle (actor)|Anthony Royle]] (Director of Amateur Production), [[Mike Quinto]] (Man in Audience), [[Jean Kitson]] (Chemist's Assistant)\n| ShortSummary    = John Burge, a pharmacist, is carrying on an affair behind his overweight wife's back.&nbsp; His lover, Frances, tells him that he must get rid of his wife.&nbsp; Mary, however, will not divorce him and Frances is issuing an ultimatum.&nbsp; He decides to put his pharmaceutical skills into play and poison his wife's chocolates.&nbsp; However, not everything will go to plan.\n| LineColor       = 060701\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 16\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|04|12|df=y}}\n| Title           = [[Taste (short story)|Taste]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Alastair Reid (director)|Alastair Reid]]\n| WrittenBy       = ''Story by'': Roald Dahl<br>''Dramatisation by'': [[Ronald Harwood]]\n